Note: ============================================================================
Note: P2-B.1 WAVE 1 BACKFILL - DISPATCHER SURFACE
Note: ============================================================================
Note:
The 18 declarations below complete the cross-platform 66-proc dispatcher API
surface for freebsd_x64. Wave 1 keeps the bare-name form to match the still
bare-name dispatcher; Wave 2 will perform the platform-prefix rename
(freebsd_x64_*). All numeric values are FreeBSD-authoritative and cited at
each declaration's @Reasoning block. Sources: FreeBSD `sys/sys/syscall.h`
(syscall numbers), `sys/sys/fcntl.h` (file mode bits), `sys/sys/mman.h`
(memory mapping bits), `sys/sys/unistd.h` (seek constants).
:End Note

Note: ============================================================================
Note: ADDITIONAL SYSCALL NUMBER ACCESSORS (DISPATCHER SURFACE)
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
The cross-platform syscall dispatcher's 66-proc surface requires SYS_EXIT_GROUP,
SYS_BRK, and SYS_SCHED_GETAFFINITY accessors on every platform module so that
caller code written against the universal dispatcher contract resolves to a
platform-correct numeric syscall number at the dispatch boundary.

FreeBSD specifics, per `sys/sys/syscall.h` in stable/14 (the LTS branch used
as the reference point in the P2-B design doc's "Per-platform syscall
inventory" table):

- SYS_EXIT_GROUP: FreeBSD has no dedicated process-group exit syscall; the
  `exit(2)` syscall (number 1) tears down the whole process address space
  including all threads sharing it. The Linux `exit_group(2)` semantic is
  the FreeBSD `exit(2)` default behaviour, so SYS_EXIT_GROUP aliases to 1.
  The P2-B design table row "exit_group" explicitly directs "(use exit)"
  for FreeBSD.
- SYS_BRK: FreeBSD inherited the historical 4.4BSD `break(2)` syscall at
  number 17. Modern FreeBSD libc no longer exposes `brk`/`sbrk` through
  this entry (the userland malloc uses `mmap` exclusively), but the
  syscall slot remains live for legacy callers and for cross-platform
  Runa code that names `SYS_BRK` via the dispatcher. The P2-B design
  table row "brk" assigns 17 for FreeBSD.
- SYS_SCHED_GETAFFINITY: FreeBSD does not implement the Linux
  `sched_getaffinity(2)` syscall. The equivalent FreeBSD facility is
  `cpuset_getaffinity(2)` (number 487), which queries the CPU set mask
  for a thread/process/cpuset object. The two APIs differ in argument
  shape (FreeBSD takes a cpu_level, cpu_which, cpu_id, setsize, mask
  tuple; Linux takes pid, cpusetsize, mask). The P2-B design row
  "sched_getaffinity" assigns "cpuset_getaffinity 487" for FreeBSD and
  caller bridging is the responsibility of the dispatcher's syscall_*
  wrapper layer, not the SYS_* accessor.

Source: FreeBSD `sys/sys/syscall.h` (stable/14 branch).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Each accessor is a nullary Process returning the constant integer value.
The bare-name dispatcher routes `SYS_EXIT_GROUP from Syscall` (etc.) to
these procs on freebsd_x64 targets. Wave 2 will rename to
`freebsd_x64_SYS_EXIT_GROUP` etc. when the dispatcher migrates to the
prefix pattern.

SYS_EXIT_GROUP returns 1 (alias to SYS_EXIT) because FreeBSD's `exit(2)`
already provides the process-wide termination semantic that Linux
`exit_group(2)` offers; no separate slot exists.

SYS_BRK returns 17, matching FreeBSD's historical `break(2)` slot. Caller
code expecting `addr=0` to query current break or a positive `addr` to
set it must understand that modern FreeBSD libc does not maintain the
break pointer through this call; direct callers issuing `syscall(SYS_BRK,
addr)` bypass libc state and may produce undefined libc-allocator
behaviour if mixed with malloc. This is a FreeBSD-platform property,
not a wrapper deficiency.

SYS_SCHED_GETAFFINITY returns 487, the FreeBSD `cpuset_getaffinity(2)`
number. Dispatcher-level wrappers that want Linux-shaped
`sched_getaffinity(pid, setsize, mask)` semantics on FreeBSD must
translate: pid maps to (CPU_LEVEL_WHICH, CPU_WHICH_PID, pid), the
remaining args map to (setsize, mask) with cpusetid set to -1
(CPUSET_INVALID). This translation is dispatcher-layer concern;
the SYS_* accessor here only reports the raw syscall number.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Constant returns; the compiler inlines each accessor at every call site,
producing zero call overhead. Do not insert caching, memoisation, or
computed branches; the value is a build-time constant of the platform
ABI and changes only on a FreeBSD major-version syscall renumbering
(none has occurred in the historical record).

In hot-path syscall sites callers may inline the numeric constant
directly into the generic `syscall_N` invocation, bypassing the
accessor entirely; the accessor exists for dispatcher contract
compliance and for symbolic source readability.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returning a syscall number constant carries no security state. Security
considerations attach to the syscall invocations themselves:

- SYS_EXIT_GROUP (= SYS_EXIT = 1): irreversible process termination. A
  caller that issues this with attacker-influenced timing can be used to
  force a denial-of-service window; sandboxed callers must run under a
  seccomp-equivalent (FreeBSD `capsicum(4)` capability mode) policy that
  governs when termination is permitted.
- SYS_BRK (= 17): brk-based heap growth is a known target for arbitrary
  read/write primitives in exploits against legacy allocators. Modern
  FreeBSD libc uses mmap and does not rely on brk; callers in safety
  critical paths should prefer `syscall_mmap(MAP_ANON|MAP_PRIVATE)` over
  brk for new allocations.
- SYS_SCHED_GETAFFINITY (= 487, cpuset_getaffinity): reading a process's
  CPU affinity mask leaks scheduling-policy information. FreeBSD permits
  the read for the calling process by default; reading another process's
  mask requires PROC_PDEATHSIG_CTL-equivalent permissions or
  matching jail/UID. The kernel enforces; the SYS_* accessor performs
  no validation.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "freebsd_x64_SYS_EXIT_GROUP" returns Integer:
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "freebsd_x64_SYS_BRK" returns Integer:
    Return 17
End Process

Process called "freebsd_x64_SYS_SCHED_GETAFFINITY" returns Integer:
    Return 487
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: FILE PERMISSION MODE CONSTANTS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
File mode constants exposed by the cross-platform dispatcher's bare-name API.
FreeBSD uses the standard POSIX `mode_t` encoding identical to Linux/Darwin:
the low 9 bits are the rwxrwxrwx permission triplet, encoded octally as
0644 (rw-r--r--) and 0755 (rwxr-xr-x). The values below are the decimal
equivalents of those octal constants, as required by the syscall ABI which
treats the mode argument as a plain integer.

Source: FreeBSD `sys/sys/stat.h` (S_IRUSR=0000400, S_IWUSR=0000200,
S_IRGRP=0000040, S_IWGRP=0000020, S_IROTH=0000004, S_IWOTH=0000002,
S_IXUSR=0000100, S_IXGRP=0000010, S_IXOTH=0000001).

Computation:
- 0644 octal = 0400|0200|0040|0004 = 256+128+32+4 = 420 decimal.
- 0755 octal = 0400|0200|0100|0040|0010|0004|0001 = 256+128+64+32+8+4+1 = 493 decimal.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Each accessor is a nullary Process returning the constant integer value.
The dispatcher's `MODE_0644 from Syscall` and `MODE_0755 from Syscall`
lookups resolve to these procs on freebsd_x64 targets via the bare-name
route established in Wave 1. Wave 2 will rename to
`freebsd_x64_MODE_0644` and `freebsd_x64_MODE_0755`. Bodies are
trivially inlinable nullary returns; no branching, no allocation,
no observable side effect.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Constant returns; compiler-inlined at the call site. No runtime cost.
Avoid wrapping these in additional indirection; the dispatcher already
selects the platform-correct value at the dispatch boundary.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returning a file permission constant carries no security state. Callers
who use the returned value as a `mode` argument to `creat(2)`,
`open(2)` with O_CREAT, `mkdir(2)`, `chmod(2)`, or `mkfifo(2)` are
responsible for ensuring the requested permission matches the intended
access policy. World-readable (0644) is appropriate for non-sensitive
data files; group-and-world-executable (0755) is appropriate for
binaries and directories. Callers handling secret material must use
restrictive modes (e.g. 0600) and not these constants.

The umask of the calling process is applied by the kernel after the
mode argument is supplied, masking off bits per the process's
`umask(2)` setting; the actual on-disk mode is (requested_mode &
~umask). Callers cannot bypass umask through these constants; an
attacker who controls umask of a child process cannot escalate via
this path.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "freebsd_x64_MODE_0644" returns Integer:
    Return 420  Note: 0644 octal = rw-r--r--
End Process

Process called "freebsd_x64_MODE_0755" returns Integer:
    Return 493  Note: 0755 octal = rwxr-xr-x
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: FILE SEEK WHENCE CONSTANTS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
The `whence` argument to `lseek(2)` selects how the supplied offset is
interpreted: SEEK_SET (0) measures from the start of the file, SEEK_CUR
(1) measures relative to the current file position, SEEK_END (2)
measures relative to end-of-file. FreeBSD inherits the standard POSIX
values defined in `sys/sys/unistd.h`, identical across all FreeBSD
architectures and matching every Unix-derivative platform back to
4.2BSD.

These values match the bare-name dispatcher's expectations and the
`syscall_lseek` wrapper's `whence` parameter. FreeBSD additionally
defines SEEK_DATA=3 and SEEK_HOLE=4 (sparse-file query) but those are
outside the 66-proc dispatcher surface and not exposed here.

Source: FreeBSD `sys/sys/unistd.h` (stable/14).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Nullary Process accessors returning the constant integer values. The
dispatcher routes `SEEK_SET from Syscall` (etc.) to this proc on
freebsd_x64 targets via the bare-name pattern still in force during
Wave 1. Bodies are non-side-effecting and trivially inlinable.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Constant returns; compiler-inlined at the call site. No runtime cost.
Avoid wrapping these in additional indirection; the dispatcher already
selects the platform-correct value at the dispatch boundary.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returning a seek-whence constant has no security implications on its
own. Callers that pass attacker-influenced `offset` values into
`lseek(2)` with these whence flags MUST validate the resulting
absolute file position against the file's permitted range; an
attacker-controlled negative offset combined with SEEK_END can yield
an unexpected position prior to file start, which `lseek(2)` rejects
with EINVAL on conforming FreeBSD kernels.

Position-truncation TOCTOU: callers that seek then read/write should
be aware that another process holding the same file descriptor (via
fork inheritance or SCM_RIGHTS passing) can independently move the
file position between the seek and the I/O syscall. Use `pread(2)`
or `pwrite(2)` (syscalls 475/476 on FreeBSD) for atomic offset+I/O
when shared-fd contention is possible.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "freebsd_x64_SEEK_SET" returns Integer:
    Return 0  Note: Seek from beginning of file
End Process

Process called "freebsd_x64_SEEK_CUR" returns Integer:
    Return 1  Note: Seek from current position
End Process

Process called "freebsd_x64_SEEK_END" returns Integer:
    Return 2  Note: Seek from end of file
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: DISPATCHER-NAMED SYSCALL WRAPPERS (syscall_<name> bare form)
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
The cross-platform syscall dispatcher exposes 10 `syscall_<name>` bare-name
procs (syscall_read, syscall_write, syscall_open, syscall_close,
syscall_exit, syscall_brk, syscall_mmap, syscall_munmap, syscall_fstat,
syscall_lseek). Each platform module must export the same names so the
dispatcher's bare-name routing can resolve to platform-correct ABI
behaviour. On FreeBSD x86-64, each wrapper routes through the correct
syscall_N generic dispatcher with the FreeBSD-authoritative SYS_*
number.

These are NOT duplicates of the higher-section `read`/`write`/`open`/...
short-name wrappers in this file: those use POSIX-style short names
for compatibility with the pre-v0.0.7.5 Runa runtime; the
`syscall_<name>` forms are what the P2-B platform-dispatch
infrastructure expects per the design's "Per-platform syscall
inventory" section.

Per-call FreeBSD syscall numbers (from `sys/sys/syscall.h` stable/14):
- syscall_read   -> SYS_READ   = 3
- syscall_write  -> SYS_WRITE  = 4
- syscall_open   -> SYS_OPEN   = 5
- syscall_close  -> SYS_CLOSE  = 6
- syscall_exit   -> SYS_EXIT   = 1
- syscall_brk    -> SYS_BRK    = 17
- syscall_mmap   -> SYS_MMAP   = 477 (FreeBSD 7+ entry; the 64-bit-clean
                                       mmap rev with `void *` return and
                                       `off_t` offset)
- syscall_munmap -> SYS_MUNMAP = 73
- syscall_fstat  -> SYS_FSTAT  = 189
- syscall_lseek  -> SYS_LSEEK  = 478 (FreeBSD 7+ entry; the 64-bit-clean
                                       lseek rev with `off_t` offset)

Source for syscall numbers: FreeBSD `sys/sys/syscall.h` (stable/14
branch). Note that FreeBSD has two `mmap` entries (197 legacy,
477 modern) and two `lseek` entries (199 legacy, 478 modern); the
dispatcher contract requires the modern entries which match the
64-bit clean ABI used by all FreeBSD platforms since 7.0 (2008).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Each wrapper computes the syscall number via the matching SYS_*
accessor (itself a constant return on freebsd_x64) and forwards
arguments to the `syscall_N` generic dispatcher matching the arity.
The generic dispatcher loads RAX with the syscall number and
RDI/RSI/RDX/R10/R8/R9 with arguments, then issues the `syscall`
instruction and returns RAX. Negative RAX values are kernel errno
indications which the wrapper propagates unchanged to the caller.

Argument-passing convention (FreeBSD x86-64 System V derivative ABI
for syscalls):
- syscall_read(fd, buffer, count)            -> SYS_READ(3) via syscall_3
- syscall_write(fd, buffer, count)           -> SYS_WRITE(4) via syscall_3
- syscall_open(filename, flags, mode)        -> SYS_OPEN(5) via syscall_3
- syscall_close(fd)                          -> SYS_CLOSE(6) via syscall_1
- syscall_exit(status)                       -> SYS_EXIT(1) via syscall_1
- syscall_brk(addr)                          -> SYS_BRK(17) via syscall_1
- syscall_mmap(addr, len, prot, flags, fd, offset)
                                             -> SYS_MMAP(477) via syscall_6
- syscall_munmap(addr, length)               -> SYS_MUNMAP(73) via syscall_2
- syscall_fstat(fd, statbuf)                 -> SYS_FSTAT(189) via syscall_2
- syscall_lseek(fd, offset, whence)          -> SYS_LSEEK(478) via syscall_3

Note on FreeBSD mmap return convention: SYS_MMAP=477 returns the mapped
address in RAX on success, or -errno on failure. The caller must
distinguish: an RAX value in the kernel-reserved high range
(0xFFFF_FFFF_FFFF_F000..0xFFFF_FFFF_FFFF_FFFF) is a negated errno;
all other values are valid user-space addresses. This is the standard
FreeBSD syscall errno convention and identical to the Linux behaviour
the dispatcher contract expects.

Note on FreeBSD fstat struct layout: FreeBSD 12+ uses a 224-byte
`struct stat` (with 64-bit ino_t and nlink_t). Callers passing
`statbuf` must reserve at least that much space; under-allocation
results in kernel memory write past the buffer end and corruption.
The wrapper does not enforce this; the dispatcher contract assumes
the caller has consulted the platform stat-struct size primitive.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Each wrapper compiles down to: load constant syscall number, marshal
arguments through stack frame to RDI..R9/RAX, issue `syscall`
instruction. Total cost is dominated by the kernel-mode trap
(~100-300 cycles on modern x86-64 with KPTI mitigations), not the
wrapper's Runa-level indirection. The wrapper itself adds 2-3
instructions of glue beyond the generic syscall_N body.

For hot-path syscall sites (e.g. read/write in tight I/O loops),
prefer calling the generic `syscall_3` directly with the SYS_*
constant inlined, avoiding the intermediate wrapper. The wrapper
exists for dispatcher contract compliance, not as a recommended
fast-path entry.

For repeated mmap/munmap of same-sized regions, prefer the
`mremap`-equivalent (FreeBSD: re-mmap with MAP_FIXED|MAP_REMAP);
the unmap+mmap pair flushes TLB entries that a remap could
preserve.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
File-descriptor and pointer arguments are passed verbatim to the
kernel. The wrapper performs no validation; the kernel enforces all
access controls (UID/GID, jail boundaries, capsicum capability
restrictions, MAC framework policy, ACLs). Callers must NOT use
these wrappers to issue syscalls on behalf of an untrusted source
without capsicum capability-mode confinement at the process level.

In particular:
- syscall_open: untrusted `filename` strings can traverse the
  filesystem subject only to DAC, jail, and capsicum policy;
  sandboxed callers must enter capability mode (`cap_enter(2)`,
  syscall 516) and use `*at` variants with a pre-opened directory
  fd to prevent path traversal.
- syscall_mmap with PROT_EXEC: writable+executable mappings are a
  W^X violation; FreeBSD's `mprotect(2)` allows downgrading from
  W to RX but not the reverse on ELF-restricted segments. Callers
  should request PROT_READ|PROT_WRITE then mprotect-up to
  PROT_EXEC after content is written.
- syscall_exit: terminates the calling process (whole address
  space). Threads do not survive; per-thread exit requires
  `thr_exit(2)` (syscall 431) directly via syscall_1.
- syscall_brk: as documented in SYS_BRK above, modern FreeBSD
  libc does not coordinate state through this entry. Mixing
  direct syscall_brk with libc malloc is undefined behaviour.

Errno propagation: kernel returns -errno in RAX for failure (with
the FreeBSD convention that errno values in the range 1..ELAST are
negated). The wrapper returns this verbatim; positive values are
syscall results (e.g. byte counts, file descriptors, addresses).
Caller MUST check the sign of the return value before treating it
as a syscall result. For mmap specifically, see the address-range
distinguishment in @Implementation above.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "freebsd_x64_syscall_read" takes fd as Integer, buffer as Integer, count as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Read from file descriptor; routes through SYS_READ (3) on freebsd_x64
    Let syscall_num be freebsd_x64_SYS_READ()
    Return freebsd_x64_syscall_3(syscall_num, fd, buffer, count)
End Process

Process called "freebsd_x64_syscall_write" takes fd as Integer, buffer as Integer, count as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Write to file descriptor; routes through SYS_WRITE (4) on freebsd_x64
    Let syscall_num be freebsd_x64_SYS_WRITE()
    Return freebsd_x64_syscall_3(syscall_num, fd, buffer, count)
End Process

Process called "freebsd_x64_syscall_open" takes filename as Integer, flags as Integer, mode as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Open file; routes through SYS_OPEN (5) on freebsd_x64
    Let syscall_num be freebsd_x64_SYS_OPEN()
    Return freebsd_x64_syscall_3(syscall_num, filename, flags, mode)
End Process

Process called "freebsd_x64_syscall_close" takes fd as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Close file descriptor; routes through SYS_CLOSE (6) on freebsd_x64
    Let syscall_num be freebsd_x64_SYS_CLOSE()
    Return freebsd_x64_syscall_1(syscall_num, fd)
End Process

Process called "freebsd_x64_syscall_exit" takes status as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Exit calling process; routes through SYS_EXIT (1) on freebsd_x64
    Let syscall_num be freebsd_x64_SYS_EXIT()
    Return freebsd_x64_syscall_1(syscall_num, status)
End Process

Process called "freebsd_x64_syscall_brk" takes addr as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Adjust legacy break pointer; routes through SYS_BRK (17) on freebsd_x64
    Let syscall_num be freebsd_x64_SYS_BRK()
    Return freebsd_x64_syscall_1(syscall_num, addr)
End Process

Process called "freebsd_x64_syscall_mmap" takes addr as Integer, length as Integer, prot as Integer, flags as Integer, fd as Integer, offset as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Map memory region; routes through SYS_MMAP (477, modern entry) on freebsd_x64
    Let syscall_num be freebsd_x64_SYS_MMAP()
    Return freebsd_x64_syscall_6(syscall_num, addr, length, prot, flags, fd, offset)
End Process

Process called "freebsd_x64_syscall_munmap" takes addr as Integer, length as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Unmap memory region; routes through SYS_MUNMAP (73) on freebsd_x64
    Let syscall_num be freebsd_x64_SYS_MUNMAP()
    Return freebsd_x64_syscall_2(syscall_num, addr, length)
End Process

Process called "freebsd_x64_syscall_fstat" takes fd as Integer, statbuf as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get file status by fd; routes through SYS_FSTAT (189) on freebsd_x64
    Let syscall_num be freebsd_x64_SYS_FSTAT()
    Return freebsd_x64_syscall_2(syscall_num, fd, statbuf)
End Process

Process called "freebsd_x64_syscall_lseek" takes fd as Integer, offset as Integer, whence as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Reposition file offset; routes through SYS_LSEEK (478, modern entry) on freebsd_x64
    Let syscall_num be freebsd_x64_SYS_LSEEK()
    Return freebsd_x64_syscall_3(syscall_num, fd, offset, whence)
End Process
